"{\n    \"analysis\": \"Based on the data, there is a clear increasing trend in the number of days above 80 degrees Fahrenheit over the years from 2024 to 2080. The data shows variability but overall, there is a noticeable upward trajectory in the projections.\",\n    \"risks\": \"The increasing number of days above 80 degrees Fahrenheit poses significant climate risks such as heat strokes, heat-related illnesses, strain on energy resources due to increased demand for cooling, negative impacts on agriculture, and worsening air quality.\",\n    \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Implement heat-resilient infrastructure such as green roofs and cool pavements to reduce urban heat island effect.\",\n        \"Promote tree planting and green spaces to provide shade and cooling in urban areas.\",\n        \"Encourage energy-efficient cooling systems and practices to reduce energy consumption during hot days.\",\n        \"Develop early warning systems and heat emergency response plans to protect vulnerable populations during extreme heat events.\",\n        \"Educate the public on heat preparedness and the importance of staying hydrated and cool during hot days.\"\n    ]\n}"